    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Nuclear energy is a critical, non-negotiable pillar of the global fight against climate change because it provides the massive, reliable baseload power needed to replace fossil fuels without emitting carbon. Proponents argue that unlike intermittent renewables like wind and solar, nuclear plants run constantly and can decarbonize heavy industries and power grids efficiently. However, opponents raise valid concerns about the catastrophic risks of meltdowns, the long-term hazards of radioactive waste disposal, and the immense financial costs and geopolitical risks associated with building new reactors. Ultimately, while the technology is complex and carries inherent dangers, the sheer scale of climate change makes nuclear power one of the few viable solutions to meet our energy demands sustainably.",
